1.2.1 Freshwater aquaculture. One sustainable solution is the development of freshwater aquaculture to meet organic status using an integrated multi-trophic aquaculture system (IMTA) approach. This can be used to commercially produce fish where the system does not discharge effluent to receiving water nor does rely on use of chemicals such as antibiotics [6]. Specifically, this is a novel peatland-based IMTA process set in the middle of Mount Lucas Wind Farm, Co. Offaly, Ireland (53°17′3″ N - 7°11′45″ W). The aquaculture system consists of four split (pill) ponds connected to an algae and duckweed lagoon with sixteen channels serving as a natural treatment system (See Fig. 1
                        ). Fish are kept at a density that does not exceed the organic farming standard (e.g., <20 kg/m−3 for perch), using screens at the D-ends of each split pond. The space between two D-end fish culture areas is also used to treat waste with free living algae in suspension. Flow in each split pond is generated and water is circulated using an airlift. Each D-end fish culture area is equipped with oxygen and temperature probes connected to paddlewheels to provide extra oxygen when necessary. The farm is designed to hold a maximum of 32,000 kg of fish. This trial IMTA system holds European perch (Perca fluviatilis), rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiis), common duckweed (Lemna minor) and gibbous duckweed (Lemna gibba) and exploits use of microalgae for waste removal. Water is only added to the system from a nearby bog river to offset evaporation and only released as a result of overflow during times of excessive rainfall. This IMTA process differs from traditional aquaculture systems that use water from natural sources (rivers, lakes, etc.). Traditional systems must also consider potential pollutants from external sources (agricultural runoff, industry waste, wastewater treatments plants). A nearby wind turbine sustainably generates all electrical needs for the trial fish farm at Mount Lucas, as shown in Fig. 1. Tables 1 and 2

                         provide physicochemical parameters from effluent sampled at Mount Lucas site that highlight efficacy of natural ecosystem remediation process.
